Articles.Content:
I think it would be pretty cool to explore Kerbal Space Program, in stereoscopic 3D (red and blue). I know VR has been mentioned before but that requires significantly more work and development than this. Would help give a sense of scale and depth especially while in orbit, landing or just in general flying.

What's everyone's thoughts?

if it could be implemented properly, that would be really cool. By properly, I mean that the actual judgement of scale and distance is intuitive enough and accurate enough for our normal 3d to work.

Although, it may be a pain to share videos if you start to play exclusively in stereoscopic.

13 minutes ago, qzgy said:

if it could be implemented properly, that would be really cool. By properly, I mean that the actual judgement of scale and distance is intuitive enough and accurate enough for our normal 3d to work.

Although, it may be a pain to share videos if you start to play exclusively in stereoscopic.

Likely just have a setting to output it to one of two monitors if players want a normal version.

1 minute ago, ZooNamedGames said:

Likely just have a setting to output it to one of two monitors if players want a normal version.

But then you would have to assume that people have two monitors, and the graphics capability to run it.

11 minutes ago, qzgy said:

But then you would have to assume that people have two monitors, and the graphics capability to run it.

Most people don't share videos either. Some do, but not every player.

I like this idea to happen but i think they should implement it now as a turn on and off feature instead of VR and when they have Developed the VR Capability , they should Absolutely , Replace it with VR . 

That's my opinion

Edited April 30, 2017 by Space_taco
But how much depth would we get? If you have a ship in orbit, all you get is a ship. It's not a character in an urban setting with city blocks extending into the horizon

I can make just about any game work with the oculus rift. They likely just won't be '3D' or well adapted. 

Most OR games just take the game window and display it as a large screen in the headset so it appears more detailed- when in reality it's just the default game window blown up to greater size and displayed in the OR. 

Its the same way YouTube displays google cardboard for normal videos.

If you have a recent Nvidia card, you can try to force stereoscopic 3D. Not all games may work properly with it though, and they don't support side-by-side 3D, so you can't just stream the display to a Cardboard-like setup.
